<div data-message-author-role="assistant" data-message-id="96c42192-8fb2-4526-8979-df18b45bc3e4" dir="auto" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal [.text-message+&]:mt-5" data-message-model-slug="gpt-4o">

<div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full break-words light markdown-new-styling">
<p data-start="0" data-end="89">As a Canadian citizen, here's what you need to know about visas for Vietnam and Thailand:</p>
<h3 data-start="91" data-end="107">
<strong data-start="95" data-end="107">Vietnam:</strong>
</h3>
<ul data-start="108" data-end="636">
<li data-start="108" data-end="636">
<p data-start="110" data-end="193">
<strong data-start="110" data-end="127">Visa Required</strong>
: Yes, Canadian passport holders 
<strong data-start="160" data-end="175">need a visa</strong>
 to enter Vietnam.
</p>
<ul data-start="196" data-end="636">
<li data-start="196" data-end="348">
<p data-start="198" data-end="348">
<strong data-start="198" data-end="208">E-visa</strong>
: You can apply for an e-visa online through the Vietnamese government website. It’s a single-entry visa that allows stays of up to 30 days.
</p>
</li>
<li data-start="351" data-end="526">
<p data-start="353" data-end="526">
<strong data-start="353" data-end="378">Visa on Arrival (VOA)</strong>
: If you are flying into Vietnam, you can apply for a Visa on Arrival, but you'll need to obtain an approval letter beforehand from a travel agency.
</p>
</li>
<li data-start="529" data-end="636">
<p data-start="531" data-end="636">
<strong data-start="531" data-end="547">Embassy Visa</strong>
: You can also apply for a traditional visa through the Vietnamese embassy if you prefer.
</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start="638" data-end="655">
<strong data-start="642" data-end="655">Thailand:</strong>
</h3>
<ul data-start="656" data-end="1017">
<li data-start="656" data-end="1017">
<p data-start="658" data-end="871">
<strong data-start="658" data-end="679">Visa Not Required</strong>
: For stays of 
<strong data-start="694" data-end="711">up to 30 days</strong>
, Canadian citizens do 
<strong data-start="734" data-end="753">not need a visa</strong>
 for tourism purposes if you are entering Thailand by air. If you're entering by land, you can stay for up to 15 days.
</p>
<ul data-start="874" data-end="1017">
<li data-start="874" data-end="1014">
<p data-start="876" data-end="1014">
<strong data-start="876" data-end="889">Extension</strong>
: If you plan to stay longer than the allowed duration, you can apply for an extension at the immigration office in Thailand.
</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1018" data-end="1166">So, you'll need a visa for Vietnam (either an e-visa or through the embassy), but you don't need one for Thailand if you're staying 30 days or less.</p>
<p data-start="1168" data-end="1291" data-is-last-node data-is-only-node>Do you know how long you'll be staying in each country? That might help narrow down what kind of visa you need for Vietnam.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

  - **Visa on Arrival (VOA)**: If you are flying into Vietnam, you can apply for a Visa on Arrival, but you'll need to obtain an approval letter beforehand from a travel agency.
  - **Embassy Visa**: You can also apply for a traditional visa through the Vietnamese embassy if you prefer.

### **Thailand:**
- **Visa Not Required**: For stays of **up to 30 days**, Canadian citizens do **not need a visa** for tourism purposes if you are entering Thailand by air. If you're entering by land, you can stay for up to 15 days.
  - **Extension**: If you plan to stay longer than the allowed duration, you can apply for an extension at the immigration office in Thailand.
  
So, you'll need a visa for Vietnam (either an e-visa or through the embassy), but you don't need one for Thailand if you're staying 30 days or less.

Do you know how long you'll be staying in each country? That might help narrow down what kind of visa you need for Vietnam.</div>

answer_text_markdown:
As a Canadian citizen, here's what you need to know about visas for Vietnam and Thailand:

### **Vietnam:** 

* **Visa Required**: Yes, Canadian passport holders **need a visa** to enter Vietnam.  
   * **E-visa**: You can apply for an e-visa online through the Vietnamese government website. Its a single-entry visa that allows stays of up to 30 days.  
   * **Visa on Arrival (VOA)**: If you are flying into Vietnam, you can apply for a Visa on Arrival, but you'll need to obtain an approval letter beforehand from a travel agency.  
   * **Embassy Visa**: You can also apply for a traditional visa through the Vietnamese embassy if you prefer.

### **Thailand:** 

* **Visa Not Required**: For stays of **up to 30 days**, Canadian citizens do **not need a visa** for tourism purposes if you are entering Thailand by air. If you're entering by land, you can stay for up to 15 days.  
   * **Extension**: If you plan to stay longer than the allowed duration, you can apply for an extension at the immigration office in Thailand.

So, you'll need a visa for Vietnam (either an e-visa or through the embassy), but you don't need one for Thailand if you're staying 30 days or less.

Do you know how long you'll be staying in each country? That might help narrow down what kind of visa you need for Vietnam.
